      "result": "\u003coutput\u003e\n{\n  \"rating\": 4,\n  \"summary\": \"The #615 GUI role-selector parity code is structurally sound. Role validation against VALID_ROLES happens server-side before any storage op; primary uniqueness is double-enforced (pre-validate 409 for aux + validate() backstop for primary); the detach scope is correctly per-agent; no secrets surface in the frontend. One warning-level TOCTOU exists in the new _persist_attachments path where the proposed attachment list is computed outside the hosts-file lock and then blindly stamped inside it.\",\n  \"findings\": [\n    {\n      \"severity\": \"warning\",\n      \"location\": \"src/clawrium/gui/routes/providers.py:524-597\",\n      \"issue\": \"TOCTOU race in attach / detach persist path. The handler reads `current` attachments from the in-memory host dict (captured before the `update_host` lock is acquired), computes `new_attachments` or `remaining`, and then calls `_persist_attachments` which passes the pre-computed list into `update_host`'s updater closure. `update_host` does re-read the hosts file inside the lock (line 155: `hosts = load_hosts()`), but the updater it applies overwrites `agents[agent_key]['providers']` with the stale pre-lock list, not the freshly-read one. Two concurrent `POST /{name}/attach` requests for different providers on the same hermes agent can therefore race: both read the same `current`, both pass the slot-conflict check, and the last writer silently drops the first writer's attachment.\",\n      \"suggestion\": \"Move the read-compute-validate sequence inside the updater function passed to `update_host`, so it executes against the freshly-loaded host within the lock. Alternatively, add an explicit check inside the updater that re-validates the proposed list against the live `agent_data['providers']` before overwriting it and raises if the invariant is violated, letting the route return 409.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"severity\": \"suggestion\",\n      \"location\": \"src/clawrium/gui/routes/providers.py:565-581\",\n      \"issue\": \"The pre-validate slot-conflict 409 only fires for aux slots (`body.role != PRIMARY_ROLE`). A second `primary` attach falls through to `validate()` which raises `AttachmentError` → HTTP 400. This is correct but asymmetric: aux conflicts get 409 (with the blocking provider named), primary conflicts get a generic 400 with an error message that doesn't name the existing primary. Operators must do a follow-up GET to identify what to detach.\",\n      \"suggestion\": \"Add an explicit primary-occupied check before the aux-slot check block (mirror the aux block pattern) and raise HTTP 409 naming the existing primary provider. This matches the documented UX contract for aux conflicts.\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"recommendations\": [\n    \"Fix TOCTOU in _persist_attachments: compute new_attachments inside the update_host updater so the read-compute-write sequence is atomic under _hosts_lock.\",\n    \"Auth boundary (no bearer on /api/providers attachment endpoints): correct per AGENTS.md SSH-is-the-boundary model. No action required — do not add a false token wall.\",\n    \"Frontend secrets: clean. Provider list exposes has_api_key boolean only; AgentAttachmentsResponse carries {name, role, model} — no credential fields.\",\n    \"Role validation ordering: correct. VALID_ROLES check at line 509 runs before any storage touch; primary uniqueness enforced server-side in validate() at line 410. No client-side-only gating.\"\n  ],\n  \"metadata\": {\n    \"files_reviewed\": 7,\n    \"domain\": \"gui-provider-attachments\"\n  }\n}\n\u003c/output\u003e",
